<p>Vowel length contrasts are neutralized in monosyllabic words with no coda consonants.<sup id="cite_ref-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D230_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D230-3"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>All vowels but <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/a/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/aː/</span> are more open in closed syllables such as in <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[ɮɛp]</span> ('to plait') and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">[xʊ́r]</span> ('to cook soup'). <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/a/</span> and <span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA">/aː/</span> are more open when following palatalized consonants.<sup id="cite_ref-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D231_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D231-4"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p><a href="/wiki/Diphthong" title="Diphthong">Diphthongs</a>, which have the same length as long vowels, consist of a non-high vowel and a high vowel:<sup id="cite_ref-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D231_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D231-4"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
