</tr>
</table>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tera_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Tone">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Tone">Tone</span></h3>
<p>Tera is a <a href="/wiki/Tonal_language" title="Tonal language" class="mw-redirect">tonal language</a>, distinguishing high, mid and low tone. Tone is not indicated orthographically since no minimal trios exist; minimal pairs can be distinguished by context.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tera_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Orthography">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Orthography">Orthography</span></h2>
<p>The first publication in Tera was <i>Labar Mbarkandu nu Yohanna Bula Ki</i>, a translation of the <a href="/wiki/Gospel_of_John" title="Gospel of John">Gospel of John</a>, which established an orthographic system. In 2004, this orthographic system was revised.<sup id="cite_ref-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D227_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Harvcoltxt.7CTench.7C2007.7Cp.3D227-0"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Tera_language&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span></h2>
